        <h2>Telecommunications Mobile Wireless Expert</h2>

        <p>Mobile wireless devices have taken the world by storm. Cell phones have been the most prevalent mobile wireless devices currently deployed on the market. This number is 10x the number of installed personal computers and 3x more than TVs globally. Communications software on these mobile devices includes both preloaded/out-of-the-box factory-installed software and post-purchased third-party software installed by the user.</p>

        <p>His background provides him with a profound depth and breadth of understanding of mobile and wireless and its underlying technologies. This understanding encompasses the mobile, wireless, cellular architectures, and the technologies they use, including Wi-Fi, cellular, Bluetooth, radio frequency identification (RFID), and near-field communication (NFC). Moreover, the understanding includes the latest wireless network protocols, including the 5G protocols used in the most up-to-date cellular networks.</p>

        <p>He has applied his research and background in mobile and wireless technologies in networking and telecommunications for various matters involving cellular, mobile, and wireless systems, including Wi-Fi, WLAN, 802.11 standard, cellular 3G, 4G, 5G, Bluetooth, and other wireless technologies. His expertise encompasses both mobile and stationary networking technologies, as well as the security aspects of these systems.</p>

        <h3>Wireless Network Protocols</h3>

        <p>Wireless networking protocols, such as Wi-Fi and WLAN (Wireless Local Area Network), allow devices to communicate wirelessly. These protocols are defined by the IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers) 802.11 standards, which include various versions such as 802.11a, 802.11b, 802.11g, 802.11n, 802.11ac, and 802.11ax (also known as Wi-Fi 6).</p>

        <p>When a device wants to connect to a wireless network, it needs to go through a process called Association. This involves the device scanning for available wireless networks, and selecting a network. The device then sends an association request to the access point (AP), the gateway between the wireless network and the wired network. The AP responds with an Association Response, and if the request is accepted, the device becomes part of the wireless network.</p>

        <p>Both wired and wireless devices can use IP and TCP/IP to communicate with each other. The main difference between wired and wireless communication is the physical medium used to transmit the data. In wired communication, data is transmitted through physical cables. At the same time, in wireless communication, data is transmitted through radio waves, which means that the data is sent over the airwaves without the need for physical cables. However, the underlying protocols, such as TCP/IP, are the same for both wired and wireless communication, meaning that devices can communicate with each other regardless of whether they are connected through a wired or wireless network.</p>

        <p>Both wired and wireless protocols can coexist within the same network. For example, a home network might have a wired Ethernet connection for a desktop computer and a wireless Wi-Fi connection for a laptop or smartphone. The devices on this network would communicate using the same IP-based protocols, regardless of whether connected through a wired or wireless connection. An access point acts as a bridge between the wired and wireless segments of the network, enabling communication between devices connected through different mediums.</p>

